,"1524–Female":"1524–Zesnulá","1547–1614":"1547–1614","1549–Female":"1549–Zesnulá","1553–1599":"1553–1599","1522–1559":"1522–1559","3 May 1559":"3. května 1559","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","1524":"1524","about 1549":"okolo 1549","1522":"1522","1599":"1599","about 1547":"okolo 1547","1553":"1553","about 1522":"okolo 1522","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","1614":"1614","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Anglie","Redenhall With Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, Anglie, United Kingdom","Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1522–3 May 1559":"omkring 1522–3. maj 1559","1524–Female":"1524–Afdød","1547–1614":"1547–1614","1549–Female":"1549–Afdød","1553–1599":"1553–1599","1522–1559":"1522–1559","3 May 1559":"3. maj 1559","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","1524":"1524","about 1549":"omkring 1549","1522":"1522","1599":"1599","about 1547":"omkring 1547","1553":"1553","about 1522":"omkring 1522","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","1614":"1614","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Redenhall With Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"about 1522–3 May 1559":"circa 1522–3 mei 1559","1524–Female":"1524–Overleden","1547–1614":"1547–1614","1549–Female":"1549–Overleden","1553–1599":"1553–1599","1522–1559":"1522–1559","3 May 1559":"3 mei 1559","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","1524":"1524","about 1549":"circa 1549","1522":"1522","1599":"1599","about 1547":"circa 1547","1553":"1553","about 1522":"circa 1522","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","1614":"1614","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Redenhall With Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"about 1522–3 May 1559":"about 1522–3 May 1559","1524–Female":"1524–Deceased","1547–1614":"1547–1614","1549–Female":"1549–Deceased","1553–1599":"1553–1599","1522–1559":"1522–1559","3 May 1559":"3 May 1559","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","1524":"1524","about 1549":"about 1549","1522":"1522","1599":"1599","about 1547":"about 1547","1553":"1553","about 1522":"about 1522","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","1614":"1614","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Redenhall With Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fuller","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a dresser of cloth, from Middle English <i>fuller</i> ‘fuller of cloth’ (partly from Old English <i>fullere</i>, partly from Old French <i>fouleor</i>, <i>foleur</i>, Latin <i>fullo</i>). Raw cloth had to be fulled, i.e. scoured, cleansed, and thickened by beating or trampling it in water, a process also known as <i>walking</i> or <i>tucking</i>, hence the surnames   Walker   and   Tucker   alongside <i>Fuller</i>. These three terms and surnames are characteristic of different parts of England. In general, in Middle English, <i>Fuller</i> is southern and eastern, while <i>Walker</i> belongs to the west and north and <i>Tucker</i> is southwestern. Compare   Fullen  .","English: variant of   Fullard   with loss of <i>-d</i>.","German (<b>Füller</b>): occupational name for a person whose work involved filling, such as a dauber, or a nickname for a gourmand or glutton. Compare   Filler  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walker","meanings":["English (mainly North and Midlands) and Scottish: occupational name for a fuller, from Middle English <i>walker</i>, Old English <i>wealcere</i> (an agent derivative of <i>wealcan</i> ‘to walk, tread’), ‘one who trampled cloth in a bath of lye or kneaded it, in order to strengthen it’. This was the regular term for the occupation during the Middle Ages in western and northern England. Compare   Fuller   and   Tucker  . As a Scottish surname it has also been used as a translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an Fhucadair</b> ‘son of the fuller’. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","History: The name was brought to North America from northern England and Scotland independently by many different bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. Samuel Walker came to Lynn, MA, <i>c.</i> 1630; Philip Walker was in Rehoboth, MA, in or before 1643. The surname was also established in VA before 1650; a Thomas Walker, born in 1715 in King and Queen County, VA, was a physician, soldier, and explorer."]},{"name":"Filler","meanings":["South German: occupational name for a flayer or skinner, from Middle High German <i>viller</i> ‘knacker’, from <i>villen</i> ‘to skin’.","Altered form of German <b>Füller</b> (see   Fuller  ).","English: variant of   Filer   1 or 2."]},{"name":"Fullen","meanings":["English: occupational name for a fuller (see   Fuller  ), from Old French <i>fulun</i> ‘fuller’.","English (Lancashire): branch of this family in Lancashire probably represents a variant of <b>Fulham</b> (see   Fullam  ), reintroduced from Ireland."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":27,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":36,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Fuller was born about 1522, in Norfolk, England. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Mrs John Fuller. He was buried in Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"about 1522–3 May 1559":"umbes 1522–3. mai 1559","1524–Female":"1524–Surnud","1547–1614":"1547–1614","1549–Female":"1549–Surnud","1553–1599":"1553–1599","1522–1559":"1522–1559","3 May 1559":"3. mai 1559","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","1524":"1524","about 1549":"umbes 1549","1522":"1522","1599":"1599","about 1547":"umbes 1547","1553":"1553","about 1522":"umbes 1522","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","1614":"1614","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Redenhall With Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1522–3 May 1559":"noin 1522–3. toukokuuta 1559","1524–Female":"1524–Kuollut","1547–1614":"1547–1614","1549–Female":"1549–Kuollut","1553–1599":"1553–1599","1522–1559":"1522–1559","3 May 1559":"3. toukokuuta 1559","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","1524":"1524","about 1549":"noin 1549","1522":"1522","1599":"1599","about 1547":"noin 1547","1553":"1553","about 1522":"noin 1522","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","1614":"1614","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Redenhall With Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1522–3 May 1559":"environ 1522–3 mai 1559","1524–F